We are asked to identify the type of acid-base disturbance using laboratory results:

- pH = 7.12 → below normal (acidemic);  
- HCO₃⁻ = 28 mM → within normal range;  
- PCO₂ – originally listed as SO mmHg but interpreted correctly as being pathologically high (hypercarbia).  

Key principle: In acute/respiratory acidosis, pH drops while HCO₃ stays unchanged because kidneys haven’t had time yet to compensate. If HCO₃ rises instead, then there’s ongoing/chronic condition where kidney adjusts via reabsorption of HCO₃– over days. However, since HCO₃ at 28 is only mildly increased beyond baseline (~22–26), it reflects minimal adjustment rather than full compensation—and doesn't meet criteria for metabolic alkalosis nor true metabolic acidosis (which needs decreased HCO₃).

So conclusion follows logically through standard interpretation rules: Severe drop in pH + preserved normo-hydrogen carbonate point strongly favors respiratory origin due to excessive CO₂ accumulation—the most probable diagnosis among all choices available under these parameters.

